 concerning these decades: the relation of the Catholic Church with the Fascist regimes and Western democracies; the attitude toward anti-Semitism and the Shoah in Europe, and in general toward the total war; the relationship of the Holy See with the new media in the mass society; the questions arisen in the after-war period such as the Christian Democratic Party in Italy; the new role of women; and anti-communism and the competition for the consensus in the social and moral order in a secularized society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aRadio broadcastingxPolitical aspectszVatican CityxHistoryy20th century. 0aRadio in propagandazVatican CityxHistoryy20th century. 0aRadio in religionxCatholic Church. 0aRadio stationszVatican CityxHistory. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xPropaganda. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xReligious aspectsxCatholic Church. 4aHistory. 4aReligion. 4aWorld War II. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War II.2bisacsh  aAnti-Semitism.  aCommunism, Radio.  aFascism, National Socialism.  aMedia.  aPius 11.  aPius 12.  aShoah.  aVatican Radio.  aWorld War II.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075168040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781531507176?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781531507176423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781531507176/original  a978-3-11-075168-0  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles